[[File:NoName - Bedtime for Democracy.jpg|thumb|Unauthorized street art in Paris in 2015 against [[Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership|TTIP]], by Brandalism activists]]
'''Brandalism''' is an anti-[[advertising]] movement founded in July 2012 in [[London]]. Twenty-six British artists ran a "[[subvertising]]" campaign, whereby they covered [[Billboard|billboard adverts]] in five English cities with art pieces.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Battersby|first1=Matilda|title=Brandalism: Street artists hijack billboards for 'subvertising campaign'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/brandalism-street-artists-hijack-billboards-for-subvertising-campaign-7953151.html|accessdate=1 March 2015|work=The Independent|date=17 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Brandalism At The London Olympics|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/marketshare/2012/08/08/brandalism-at-the-london-olympics/|website=Forbes|accessdate=1 March 2015|date=8 August 2012}}</ref> In May 2014, 40 Brandalism activists replaced 365 outdoor advertisements in 10 British cities, at bus stops and elsewhere, with [[monochrome]] art. The posters were intended to evoke an anti-advertising sentiment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blazenhoff|first1=Rusty|title='Brandalism' rampage leaves subversive damage in its wake|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/brandalism-rampage-leaves-subversive-damage-in-its-wake/|accessdate=1 March 2015|work=CNET|date=21 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Brandalism 2014: 40 street artists. 10 cities. 365 ad takeovers. 2 days.|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lKRmVwqhEdE|website=YouTube|accessdate=1 March 2015|date=12 May 2014}}</ref>

